ğŸ Quick Interview Answer

MySQL (InnoDB) uses a B+Tree for indexes.

The primary key index is a clustered B+Tree where leaf nodes store full row data.

Secondary indexes are non-clustered B+Trees where leaf nodes store the primary key as a pointer.

B+Trees are used because they minimize disk I/O by keeping the tree shallow and enabling fast range queries.



ğŸ” 1. Data Storage Difference
B-Tree
Internal Node:
   [K1 | P1] [K2 | P2 | Data2] [K3 | P3 | Data3]


Data can appear in any node.

B+ Tree
Internal Node:
   [K1 | P1] [K2 | P2] [K3 | P3]

Leaf Node:
   [K1, Data1] - [K2, Data2] - [K3, Data3] (linked list)


Internal nodes = keys only

Leaf nodes = key + full row pointer

ğŸ” 2. Performance Differences
âœ”ï¸ Point Lookup

B-Tree may find data early â†’ slightly faster.

B+ Tree always goes to leaf â†’ consistent lookup time.

âœ”ï¸ Range Scans

B+ Tree wins â€” massively.

Range query = traverse leaf linked list â†’ O(k) for k results.

Thatâ€™s why databases use B+ Trees




âœ… B-Tree vs B+ Tree â€” Key Differences
Feature	        B-Tree	                                            B+ Tree
Data storage	Keys + data stored in both internal & leaf nodes	Keys stored in internal nodes, data only stored in leaf nodes
